o | Jell-o, Jello, or jello | jelly | jelly |- | cookie | cookie (unless referring to tea biscuits, for example) | biscuit | biscuit |- | [[Cookbook:Graham Cracker|graham cracker]] | Graham cracker or [[Cookbook:Digestive Biscuit|digestive biscuit]] [[Cookbook:International food terms#Digestive Biscuits and Graham Crackers|(Note)]] | [[Cookbook:Digestive Biscuit|digestive biscuit]] [[Cookbook:International food terms#Digestive Biscuits and Graham Crackers|(Note)]] |digestive biscuit |- | colspan=4 align=center| '''Techniques''' |- | [[Cookbook:Broiling|broiling]] | grilling | [[Cookbook:Grilling|grilling]] | grilling |- |}
==== Digestive Biscuits and Graham Crackers ====
These two items are fairly different, but are used similarly (e.g. to make crumb crusts for a cheesecake). Graham crackers are sweeter, and are available in different flavors, e.g. [[Cookbook:Cinnamon|cinnamon]], chocolate. Digestive biscuits are richer, and while slightly sweet, are often used eaten with cheese. They are also available coated on one side with milk or dark [[Cookbook:Chocolate|chocolate]].
==== Chips and French Fries (Australia) ==== In Australia, the term "chips" is generally used, but the term "French fries" is used to describe very finely cut chips (about 1/5" across.)
==== Cornflour (Australia) ==== In Australia (and New Zealand?), cornflour is frequently made from wheat. [[w:Food Standards Australia New Zealand|FSANZ]] regulations require such cornflour to declare that it contains wheat and gluten, and it is usually described as wheaten cornflour. There are some brands of cornflour that are made from maize, however.
